Title: Data Analyst
 Unit: Court Advocacy Supervised Release Program
 Reports to: Director of Compliance
 Status: Full Time; Regular; Non-Exempt
 Location: Bronx Court and Bronx Community Office
 Days/Hours: Monday-Friday 9am-5pm

 Position Summary: 
Supervised Release offers an alternative to jail, providing pretrial supervision, case management, and voluntary social services to people charged with misdemeanor and non-violent felony offenses. Program participants are monitored to ensure their appearance at court dates, and they receive referrals to community-based programming. Under the Supervised Release program (SRP), the Data Analyst (DA) will support the program through evaluation of data related to service delivery and outcomes. The position involves identifying and determining data points for collection, working with internal data and IT departments to ensure data collection points are available within the database, generating routine and ad-hoc reports that support the program by monitoring activities, contract performance and program milestones.
 Mission, Culture and Fit 
The DA needs to match the mission and culture of Fortune, including, meeting a client there they are at; engaging participants with a non-judgmental, inclusive attitude; holding space for trauma associated with criminal justice involvement and incarceration; and helping them to believe in their power to change.
 Essential Duties and Responsibilities: 

Directly, as well as through other relevant staff, run reports and conduct ongoing internal and external analyses, as well as various external contract databases for departments’ related contracts and services;
 Engage in process documentation, staff training and regular quality assurance monitoring to ensure accurate database entries;
 Advise the SRP management team on performance relative to contract goals, required level of client service, and activities in order to help units produce timely outcomes and achieve requires rates and levels of performance;
 Engage in data analysis and reporting, data visualization, research and evaluation, and development of appropriate qualitative and quantitative methodologies;
 Prepare internal quality assurance reports and surveys (as requested by unit management) for the purpose of monitoring program performance, fidelity to practice, client satisfaction, etc.;
 Represent SRP in board report process and conducting reporting and data analysis requested by senior management;
 Collaborate with Court Advocates, Case Managers and Clinical Case Coordinators;
 Ensure accurate and timely data entry of all client information into the agency’s database;
 Monitor participants attendance and compliance with supervision requirements;
 Participate in case conferences for optimum collaboration among internal programs and external agencies;
 Attend and participate in all necessary SRP meetings, conferences, and trainings;
 Engage in his/her own ongoing professional development; and
 Additional responsibilities as required.


 Qualifications: 

Associate’s degree in public health, human services, criminal justice, sociology or related field with a strong background in statistical analysis and/or data management. Bachelor’s or Master’s degree a plus;
 Must have a thorough knowledge of MS Office, including Excel at an advanced level that includes the utilization of the Analysis Toolpak;
 A minimum of two years relevant work experience, preferably in a nonprofit social service setting;
 Must be detail-oriented with superior analytical skills. Ability to do big picture thinking and solve problems in a way that is creative and collaborative;
 Although not required, knowledge of and proficiency in the following will be useful: CaseWorthy, query construction and Visual Basic;
 Experience with quality assurance and/or quality improvement;
 Ability to work with people from diverse backgrounds in a culturally-competent manner;
 Strong written and verbal communication skills; and


 We seek talented, dedicated individuals from all walks of life who possess a strong commitment to this mission. Relevant personal experience is a plus.

 Travel Requirements: May require travel to community-based sites.
 Physical Demands: To perform this job successfully, an individual must be able to perform each essential duty satisfactorily. The responsibilities and requirements listed are representative of the knowledge, skills, minimum education, training, licensing, experience and/or ability required. Reasonable accommodations may be made to enable individuals with disabilities to perform the essential functions of the job.
 The Fortune Society is an Equal Opportunity Employer. All qualified applicants will be afforded equal employment opportunities without discrimination because of conviction history, race, religion/creed, color, national origin, sex, age, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity, military status, predisposing genetic characteristics, victim of domestic violence status or marital status.
